<br>
<br>
Bush seizes initiative again in war on terrorism.<br>
<br>
<br>
WASHINGTON -- Rattled by new revelations of anti-terrorism intelligence failings and confronted by fresh partisan fights over what to do about it, the Bush administration responded Thursday with a sweeping move toward a wartime footing. <br>
   &quot;All in our government have learned a great deal since Sept. 11, and we must act on every lesson,&quot; President Bush said in a 12-minute speech televised nationally. <br>
   Bush described the move to create a Cabinet-level Department of Homeland Security as the biggest government reorganization since the beginning of the Cold War. <br>
   It is aimed at overcoming growing doubts about the competence of the U.S. law enforcement and intelligence services, and turning the political focus from past failures to future threats. <br>
   Whether Bush is successful in doing either is left immediately to Congress, which must approve the new department. Over the long term, the judgment will be whether the new infrastructure will prevent future attacks. <br>
   The administration's Cold War comparisons suggest that the latter judgment will not be known for years, perhaps decades. <br>
   If successful, the reorganization could drastically alter the anti-terrorism faces emanating from the Bush White House, replacing the embattled images of FBI Director Robert Mueller and Attorney General John Ashcroft with the relatively scar-free Tom Ridge, the director of homeland security. <br>
   White House officials made clear Thursday that Ridge, a popular former governor of Pennsylvania and a decorated Vietnam veteran, will run point in the administration's efforts to get swift congressional approval. <br>
   In a policy sense, the reorganization would turn some of the high-profile aspects of Ashcroft's job -- such as border security -- over to the more prominent Cabinet-level Department of Homeland Security. <br>
   Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Flint, said: &quot;I think that it's the proper way to move. We need coordination and communication. <br>
   &quot;I think we can do a much better job providing homeland security if they had it under one umbrella with a person who has that responsibility.&quot; <br>
   Bush has had prolonged high approval ratings that have surprised even his own pollsters and advisers. <br>
   But the political pressure on him has increased as the CIA and FBI have been increasingly subjected to second-guessing and questioning from political foes, including some who may run against Bush if he seeks re-election in 2004. <br>
   And Democrats had become increasingly critical of Ridge's unfocused, largely advisory role. <br>
   Among the more vocal proponents of a Cabinet-level Department of Homeland Security has been Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., who is traveling and fund-raising like a man thinking seriously about running for president. <br>
   Another potential 2004 Bush foe, Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle, has called for an elevated Homeland Security structure and an independent commission to look into pre-Sept. 11 intelligence failures. <br>
   As news of the new Cabinet department came out, the administration batted down any attempt to politicize reaction to the move, instead framing it historically, in Cold War proportions. <br>
   White House officials said the reorganization is the most sweeping since 1947 when Harry Truman confronted the growing threat of communism after World War II. <br>
   &quot;It's all part of the going from a peacetime society to a society that's mobilizing for war,&quot; said White House press secretary Ari Fleischer. <br>
   Although the Bush White House had long resisted making Ridge's job Cabinet-level, administration officials contended Thursday that Bush, Ridge and others have been secretly considering such a move for months. <br>
   The administration, too, tried to bat down the appearance that it was trying to change the subject from the finger-pointing between the FBI and the CIA, and any collateral political damage that could hurt Bush or his party. <br>
   &quot;It's just so much bigger than that,&quot; Fleischer said. &quot;Go back to '47 (and Truman's Cold War moves). This is a major reorganization.&quot; <br>
   Bush, elected as a small-government Republican, now confronts the reality that he wants to preside over a concentration of federal power rarely rivaled in American history. <br>
   His aides tried to head off criticism from small-government conservatives by arguing that Bush is not talking about bigger government but rather more efficient national security. <br>
   Fleischer used the term &quot;fusion&quot; to describe the changes -- an interesting choice of words for an office whose stated goals include preventing the fission nightmare of nuclear terrorism. <br>
